 Egypt, {{circa}} 1167\u201368\n\n;Texts by Maimonides\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080703012045/http://www.derushapublishing.com/siddur-mesorath-moshe.shtml Siddur Mesorath Moshe], a prayerbook based on the early Jewish liturgy as found in Maimonides's Mishne Tora\n* [http://www.mechon-mamre.org/e/e0000.htm Rambam's introduction to the Mishneh Torah (English translation])\n* [http://www.daat.ac.il/daat/mahshevt/hakdama/tohen-m-2.htm Rambam's introduction to the Commentary on the Mishnah (Hebrew language|Hebrew Fulltext)]\n* [http://www.sacred-texts.com/jud/gfp/index.htm The Guide For the Perplexed by Moses Maimonides translated into English by Michael Friedl\u00e4nder]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061212182013/http://jnul.huji.ac.il/dl/mss/html/rambam_l.htm Writings of Maimonides; manuscripts and early print editions. Jewish National and University Library]\n* [http://www.kb.dk/permalink/2006/manus/293/ Facsimile edition of Moreh Nevukhim/The Guide for the Perplexed (illuminated Hebrew manuscript, Barcelona, 1347\u201348). The Royal Library, Copenhagen]\n* [http://www.lib.cam.ac.uk/Taylor-Schechter/maimonides-exhibition.html University of Cambridge Library collection] of Judeo-Arabic letters and manuscripts written by or to Maimonides. It includes the last letter his brother David sent him before drowning at sea.\n* A. Ashur, [http://www.lib.cam.ac.uk/Taylor-Schechter/fotm/march-2014/ A newly discovered medical recipe written by Maimonides]\n* M.A Friedman and A. Ashur, [http://www.lib.cam.ac.uk/Taylor-Schechter/fotm/may-2012/ A newly-discovered autograph responsum of Maimonides]\n*{{prdl}}\n\n{{Rabbinical eras timeline|1138|1204|Maimonides}}\n{{Medieval Philosophy}}\n{{philosophy of religion}}\n{{Social and political philosophy}}\n{{Islamic medicine}}\n{{Aristotelianism}}\n{{Rishonim}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maimonides}}\n[[Category:Maimonides| ]]\n[[Category:1138 births]]\n[[Category:1204 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from C\u00f3rdoba, Spain]]\n[[Category:Medieval Jewish physicians of Spain]]\n[[Category:Medieval Jewish physicians of Egypt]]\n[[Category:Physicians of medieval Islam]]\n[[Category:Aristotelian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of Judaism]]\n[[Category:Sephardi rabbis]]\n[[Category:Egyptian rabbis]]\n[[Category:Spanish rabbis]]\n[[Category:Spanish refugees]]\n[[Category:Jewish refugees]]\n[[Category:12th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:13th-century rabbis]]\n[[Category:Rishonim]]\n[[Category:12th-century Jewish theologians]]\n[[Category:12th-century physicians]]\n[[Category:Court physicians]]\n[[Category:12th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:13th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:University of al-Qarawiyyin alumni]]\n[[Category:Medieval Jewish astronomers]]\n[[Category:Jewish astronomers]]\n[[Category:Exponents of Jewish law]]\n[[Category:Commentaries on the Mishnah]]\n[[Category:12th-century Arabic writers]]\n[[Category:12th-century Al-Andalus people]]\n[[Category:Judeo-Arabic writers]]\n[[Category:Jewish ethicists]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of Al-Andalus]]\n", "name_user": "Urenob", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e13 principles of faith:Minor edit noting some ambiguity regarding Mamonides lasting perspective.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maimonides"}
{"title_page": "Bashir Dalhatu", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Bashir Dalhatu\n| office4             = [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria| Minister of Transport and Aviation]]\n| preceded2           = [[Baba Gana Kingibe]]\n| party               = [[National Party of Nigeria]]<br>(1979\u20131983)<br>[[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)| Peoples Democratic Party]]<br>(founding member)<br>[[All Nigeria Peoples Party]]<br> (until 2006)<br>[[Advanced Congress of Democrats]]<br>(March\u2013September 2006)\n<br>[[Action Congress of Nigeria]]<br>(2006\u20132007)\n| alma_mater          = [[Ahmadu Bello University]]\n| death_place         = \n| birth_place         = [[Dutse]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Dutse]], [[Jigawa State]], Nigeria)\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1949|11|12}}\n| term_end4           = November 1993\n| term_start4         = August 1993\n| president4          = [[Ernest Shonekan]]\n| successor3          = [[Baba Gana Kingibe]]\n| image               = \n| term_end3           = 1998\n| term_start3         = 1993\n| president3          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| office3             = [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]]\n| successor2          = Musa Yakubu\n| term_end2           = 1998\n| term_start2         = 1997\n| president2          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| office2             = [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]]\n| honorific_prefix    = [[Vizier|Waziri]]\n}}\n'''Bashir Dalhatu''' (born 12 November 1949) is a Nigerian lawyer, civil servant and politician who served in the [[Cabinet of Ernest Shonekan|Interim National Government]] as [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Transport and Aviation]] in 1993, [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1993 to 1997; and [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1997 to 1998 in General [[Sani Abacha]]'s government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/199906170283.html|title=Nigeria: Abacha's Son-In-Law|last=|first=|date=|website=Tempo (Lagos)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nBashir Dalhatu was born in [[Dutse]] on November 12, 1949. He attended Rumfa College in Kano. In 1972, he received a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[law]] from the [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]], and was subsequently called to the [[Nigerian Bar Association|Nigerian Bar]] in 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leadership.ng/2019/11/15/pmb-greets-wazirin-dutse-bashir-dalhatu-on-70th-birthday/|title=PMB Greets Wazirin Dutse, Bashir Dalhatu On 70th Birthday|last=Nda-Isiah|first=Jonathan|date=15 November 2019|website=Leadership|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAfter a seven-year sojourn in the Kano State civil service, where he worked in the administrative cadre as assistant secretary in both the Ministry of Works and Survey and Ministry of Agriculture, before moving to the Ministry of Justice as state counsel. \n\nIn 1978, he was elected into the Constituent Assembly that produced the [[Constitution of Nigeria#1979 constitution (Second Republic)|1979 Constitution]]. At the conclusion of the assembly, he became one of the founding members of the [[National Party of Nigeria]] (NPN) where, between 1979 and 1983, he was the Kano State assistant secretary, state secretary and later, assistant national legal advisor. \n\nIn 1993, Dalhatu served in the [[Cabinet of Ernest Shonekan|Interim National Government]] as [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Transport and Aviation]]. He was also government minister in General Sani Abacha as [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1993 to 1997; and [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1997 to 1998, and later married Abacha's daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/199907150234.html|title=Nigeria: What Looting Has Joined Together...|last=|first=|date=12 July 1999|website=Tempo (Lagos)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe later became a founding member of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Peoples Democratic Party]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2008/12/30/pdp-and-2011-challenge-any-hope-nigeria|title=PDP and the 2011 Challenge - Any Hope for Nigeria?|last=BabaGboin|date=2008-12-30|website=Sahara Reporters|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> before leaving to contest for the Governor of Jigawa under the All Nigeria Peoples Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/200302060289.html|title=Court Declares Dalhatu Jigawa ANPP Candidate|last=Sanda|first=Juclit|date=6 February 2003|website=ThisDay|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 2006, in opposition to President [[Olusegun Obasanjo]], Dalhatu founded the [[Advanced Congress of Democrats]], before later merging the party with the [[Action Congress of Nigeria]], where he was the national secretary until resigning in 2007, after the party refused to join the President [[Umaru Musa Yar'Adua|Umaru Yar'Adua]]'s national government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/50c846b52.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Nigeria: The Action Congress of Nigeria (ACN), including its structure, name of president and principal leaders; treatment of its members by the authorities (2008-February 2012)|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He was as a member of the [[2014 National Conference, Nigeria|2014 National Conference]]. In 2018, he was became the [[Vizier|Waziri]] (chief adviser to the Emir) of the [[Dutse|Dutse Emirate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/wazirin-dutse-didnt-attain-status-by-accident.html|title=\u2018Wazirin Dutse didn\u2019t attain status by accident\u2019|last=Mudashir|first=Ismail|date=2018-12-08|website=Daily Trust|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|3}}<br />{{Interior Ministers of Nigeria}}<br />\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n| name                = Bashir Dalhatu\n| office4             = [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria| Minister of Transport and Aviation]]\n| preceded2           = [[Baba Gana Kingibe]]\n| party               = [[National Party of Nigeria]]<br>(1979\u20131983)<br>[[Peoples Democratic Party (Nigeria)| Peoples Democratic Party]]<br>(founding member)<br>[[All Nigeria Peoples Party]]<br> (until 2006)<br>[[Advanced Congress of Democrats]]<br>(March\u2013September 2006)\n<br>[[Action Congress of Nigeria]]<br>(2006\u20132007)\n| alma_mater          = [[Ahmadu Bello University]]\n| death_place         = \n| birth_place         = [[Dutse]], [[Northern Region, Nigeria|Northern Region]], [[British Nigeria]]<br>(now [[Dutse]], [[Jigawa State]], Nigeria)\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1949|11|12}}\n| term_end4           = November 1993\n| term_start4         = August 1993\n| president4          = [[Ernest Shonekan]]\n| successor3          = [[Baba Gana Kingibe]]\n| image               = \n| term_end3           = 1998\n| term_start3         = 1993\n| president3          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| office3             = [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]]\n| successor2          = Musa Yakubu\n| term_end2           = 1998\n| term_start2         = 1997\n| president2          = [[Sani Abacha]]\n| office2             = [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]]\n| honorific_prefix    = [[Vizier|Waziri]]\n}}\n'''Bashir Dalhatu''' (born 12 November 1949) is a Nigerian lawyer, civil servant and politician who served in the [[Cabinet of Ernest Shonekan|Interim National Government]] as [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Transport and Aviation]] in 1993, [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1993 to 1997; and [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1997 to 1998 in General [[Sani Abacha]]'s government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/199906170283.html|title=Nigeria: Abacha's Son-In-Law|last=|first=|date=|website=Tempo (Lagos)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n== Life ==\nBashir Dalhatu was born in [[Dutse]] on November 12, 1949. He attended Rumfa College in Kano. In 1972, he received a [[bachelor's degree]] in [[law]] from the [[Ahmadu Bello University]] in [[Zaria]], and was subsequently called to the [[Nigerian Bar Association|Nigerian Bar]] in 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leadership.ng/2019/11/15/pmb-greets-wazirin-dutse-bashir-dalhatu-on-70th-birthday/|title=PMB Greets Wazirin Dutse, Bashir Dalhatu On 70th Birthday|last=Nda-Isiah|first=Jonathan|date=15 November 2019|website=Leadership|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAfter a seven-year sojourn in the Kano State civil service, where he worked in the administrative cadre as assistant secretary in both the Ministry of Works and Survey and Ministry of Agriculture, before moving to the Ministry of Justice as state counsel. \n\nIn 1978, he was elected into the Constituent Assembly that produced the [[Constitution of Nigeria#1979 constitution (Second Republic)|1979 Constitution]]. At the conclusion of the assembly, he became one of the founding members of the [[National Party of Nigeria]] (NPN) where, between 1979 and 1983, he was the Kano State assistant secretary, state secretary and later, assistant national legal advisor. \n\nIn 1993, Dalhatu served in the [[Cabinet of Ernest Shonekan|Interim National Government]] as [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Transport and Aviation]]. He was also government minister in General Sani Abacha as [[Federal Ministries of Nigeria|Minister of Power and Steel]] from 1993 to 1997; and [[Federal Ministry of Interior (Nigeria)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] from 1997 to 1998, and later married Abacha's daughter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/199907150234.html|title=Nigeria: What Looting Has Joined Together...|last=|first=|date=12 July 1999|website=Tempo (Lagos)|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe later became a founding member of the [[People's Democratic Party (Nigeria)|Peoples Democratic Party]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://saharareporters.com/2008/12/30/pdp-and-2011-challenge-any-hope-nigeria|title=PDP and the 2011 Challenge - Any Hope for Nigeria?|last=BabaGboin|date=2008-12-30|website=Sahara Reporters|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> before leaving to contest for the Governor of Jigawa under the All Nigeria Peoples Party.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/200302060289.html|title=Court Declares Dalhatu Jigawa ANPP Candidate|last=Sanda|first=Juclit|date=6 February 2003|website=ThisDay|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He was also the pioneer national secretary of the defunct [[Action Congress of Nigeria]] (ACN), he resigned in 2007, after the party refused to join the coalition government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refworld.org/docid/50c846b52.html|title=Refworld {{!}} Nigeria: The Action Congress of Nigeria (ACN), including its structure, name of president and principal leaders; treatment of its members by the authorities (2008-February 2012)|last=Refugees|first=United Nations High Commissioner for|website=Refworld|language=en|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref> He was as a member of the [[2014 National Conference, Nigeria|2014 National Conference]]. In 2018, he was became the [[Vizier|Waziri]] (chief adviser to the Emir) of the [[Dutse|Dutse Emirate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailytrust.com.ng/wazirin-dutse-didnt-attain-status-by-accident.html|title=\u2018Wazirin Dutse didn\u2019t attain status by accident\u2019|last=Mudashir|first=Ismail|date=2018-12-08|website=Daily Trust|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|3}}<br />{{Interior Ministers of Nigeria}}<br />\n", "name_user": "Zerzuran", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bashir_Dalhatu"}
{"title_page": "WF postcode area", "text_new": "{{short description|Postcode area within the United Kingdom}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK postcode area|area_code=WF}}\nThe '''WF postcode area''', also known as the '''Wakefield postcode area''',<ref>Royal Mail, ''Address Management Guide'', (2004)</ref> is a group of 17 postcode districts in north-east England, which are subdivisions of eleven [[post town]]s. These cover much of southern and eastern [[West Yorkshire]] (including [[Wakefield]], [[Pontefract]], [[Dewsbury]], [[Batley]], [[Castleford]], [[Heckmondwike]], [[Knottingley]], [[Liversedge]], [[Mirfield]], [[Normanton, West Yorkshire|Normanton]] and [[Ossett]]), plus small parts of [[South Yorkshire|South]] and [[North Yorkshire]].\n\n__TOC__\n{{clear}}\n\n==Coverage==\nThe approximate coverage of the postcode districts:\n\n{{postcode area table start}}\n|-\n! WF1\n| WAKEFIELD\n|  [[Agbrigg]], Belle Vue, Eastmoor, Kirkthorpe, Newton Hill, [[Outwood, West Yorkshire|Outwood]], [[Wakefield|Wakefield City Centre]]\n| [[City of Wakefield|Wakefield]]\n|-\n! WF2\n| WAKEFIELD\n| [[Alverthorpe]], Carr Gate, Flanshaw, Hall Green, [[Kirkhamgate]], [[Kettlethorpe, West Yorkshire|Kettlethorpe]], Lupset, Portobello, [[Newmillerdam]], [[Sandal Magna|Sandal]], Thornes, [[Walton, Wakefield|Walton (Wakefield)]], [[Wrenthorpe]], Woolgreaves, Peacock, Pledwick\n| Wakefield\n|-\n! WF3\n| WAKEFIELD\n| [[Carlton, Rothwell|Carlton]], [[East Ardsley]], [[Lofthouse, West Yorkshire|Lofthouse]], Lofthouse Gate, [[Robin Hood, West Yorkshire|Robin Hood]],  [[Stanley, West Yorkshire|Stanley]], [[Thorpe on the Hill, West Yorkshire|Thorpe]], [[Tingley]], [[West Ardsley]]\n| [[City of Leeds|Leeds]], Wakefield\n|-\n! WF4\n| WAKEFIELD\n| Crigglestone, [[Crofton, West Yorkshire|Crofton]], [[Durkar]], [[Flockton]], [[Havercroft]], [[Horbury]], [[Netherton, Wakefield|Netherton]], New Crofton, [[Ryhill]], [[West Bretton]], [[Woolley, West Yorkshire|Woolley]] \n| Wakefield, [[Kirklees]]\n|-\n! WF5\n| OSSETT\n| [[Gawthorpe, Wakefield|Gawthorpe]], [[Healey, Ossett|Healey]], [[Ossett]] (very small area around Wakefield Road falls in the Kirklees district)\n| Wakefield, Kirklees\n|-\n! WF6\n| NORMANTON\n| [[Altofts]], [[Normanton, West Yorkshire|Normanton]]\n| Wakefield\n|-\n! WF7\n| PONTEFRACT\n| [[Ackworth, West Yorkshire|Ackworth Moor Top]], [[Ackton]], [[Featherstone]], [[Purston Jaglin]], [[Streethouse]]\n| Wakefield\n|-\n! WF8\n| PONTEFRACT\n| [[Darrington, West Yorkshire|Darrington]], [[Kirk Smeaton]], [[Pontefract]] (Monkhill), [[Thorpe Audlin]] \n| Wakefield, [[Selby District|Selby]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Doncaster|Doncaster]]\n|-\n! WF9\n| PONTEFRACT\n| [[Badsworth]], [[Fitzwilliam, West Yorkshire|Fitzwilliam]], [[Hemsworth]], [[Kinsley, West Yorkshire|Kinsley]], [[South Elmsall]], [[South Kirkby]], [[Upton, West Yorkshire|Upton]], [[Wentbridge]]\n| Wakefield, Doncaster\n|-\n! WF10\n| CASTLEFORD\n| Airedale, [[Allerton Bywater]], [[Castleford]], [[Glasshoughton]], [[Ledston]], [[New Fryston]]\n| Wakefield, Leeds\n|-\n! WF11\n| KNOTTINGLEY\n| [[Brotherton]], [[Byram, North Yorkshire|Byram]], [[Cridling Stubbs]], [[Fairburn, North Yorkshire|Fairburn]], Kellingley, [[Knottingley]] \n| Wakefield, Selby \n|-\n! WF12\n| DEWSBURY\n| [[Chickenley]], [[Dewsbury]], [[Savile Town]], Shaw Cross, [[Thornhill, West Yorkshire|Thornhill]], [[Thornhill Lees]]\n| Kirklees, Wakefield\n|-\n! WF13\n| DEWSBURY\n| [[Dewsbury Moor]], [[Ravensthorpe, Dewsbury|Ravensthorpe]]\n| Kirklees\n|-\n! WF14\n| MIRFIELD\n| Hopton, [[Mirfield]]\n| Kirklees\n|-\n! WF15\n| LIVERSEDGE\n| [[Roberttown]], [[Liversedge]]\n| Kirklees\n|-\n\n! WF16\n| HECKMONDWIKE\n| [[Heckmondwike]]\n| Kirklees\n|-\n! WF17\n| BATLEY\n| [[Birstall, West Yorkshire|Birstall]], [[Batley]], [[Staincliffe]]\n| Kirklees\n|-\n! style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|WF90\n| style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|WAKEFIELD\n| style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|''[[Redcats]]''\n| style=\"background:#FFFFFF;\"|''non-geographic''<ref name=\"nongeo1207\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.poweredbypaf.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/12July_current_non-geos-original.pdf |format=PDF |title=Non Geographic Codes |publisher=Royal Mail Address Management Unit |date=July 2012 |accessdate=20 December 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120916141140/http://www.poweredbypaf.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/12July_current_non-geos-original.pdf |archive-date=16 September 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Map==\n{{Attached KML|display=inline}}\n{{Postcode area imagemap|map=WF postcode area|size=550x330px}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Postcode Address File]]\n*[[List of postcode areas in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.poweredbypaf.com/ Royal Mail's Postcode Address File]\n*[http://www.poweredbypaf.com/how-the-royal-mail-postcode-address-file-paf-helps-organisations-verify-their-customers-identities/ A quick introduction to Royal Mail's Postcode Address File (PAF)]\n\n{{Postcode areas in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:City of Wakefield]]\n[[Category:Postcode areas covering Yorkshire and the Humber]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Postcode area within the United Kingdom}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK postcode area|area_code=WF}}\nThe '''WF postcode area''', also known as the '''Wakefield postcode area''',<ref>Royal Mail, ''Address Management Guide'', (2004)</ref> is a group of 17 postcode districts in north-east England, which are subdivisions of eleven [[post town]]s. These cover much of southern and eastern [[West Yorkshire]] (including [[Wakefield]], [[Pontefract]], [[Dewsbury]], [[Batley]], [[Castleford]], [[Heckmondwike]], [[Knottingley]], [[Liversedge]], [[Mirfield]], [[Normanton, West Yorkshire|Normanton]] and [[Ossett]]), plus small parts of [[South Yorkshire|South]] and [[North Yorkshire]].\n\n__TOC__\n{{clear}}\n\n==Coverage==\nThe approximate coverage of the postcode districts:\n\n{{post